---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const url = (p: string) => `${base.replace(/\/$/, "")}/${p.replace(/^\//, "")}`;
---
<BaseLayout title="OpenIT — an IT helpdesk. Claude Code as the Operating System.">
  <h1>An IT helpdesk.<br />Claude Code as the Operating System.</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    The control plane for every system IT runs — tickets, knowledge, agents,
    reports, integrations — authored by Claude Code as plain files in your
    git repo.
  </p>

  <div class="cta-row">
    <a href={url("/download")} class="btn">
      Download for macOS
      <span class="sub">Beta &middot; Apple Silicon + Intel</span>
    </a>
    <a href="https://github.com/pinkfish-ai/openit-app" class="btn secondary">View on GitHub</a>
  </div>

  <h2>A different substrate</h2>
  <p>
    Legacy ITSM keeps your config in the vendor's database, behind a clicky
    admin UI. The new agentic wave bolts an AI chat layer on top of the same
    database. Either way, you're inside the vendor's model of IT.
  </p>
  <p>
    OpenIT moves the substrate. Your service desk is <strong>files in git,
    authored by Claude Code</strong> — every skill, every MCP, every model
    setting you'd get in a terminal. No proprietary agent to learn.
  </p>

  <h2>What that unlocks</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>One conversation, every system.</strong> Tail AD logs, query
      Okta, pivot to Jira, draft a fix. Claude Code is your IT command line.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Any report, on demand.</strong> No fixed dashboards. Describe
      what you want; Claude writes it.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Connectors you can extend.</strong> Catalog missing something?
      Claude writes the integration. Ship the same day.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Answer once.</strong> Every escalated ticket leaves a KB article
      behind. The next person gets the answer instantly.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Change control like code.</strong> Branch, PR, merge,
      <code>git revert</code>. Rollback in seconds — not a vendor support
      ticket.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Authored on your machine. Runs in production.</h2>
  <p>
    OpenIT pins a real Claude Code session to your project folder, so the
    whole helpdesk can be built, tested, and administered locally — against
    real integrations, no paid sandbox tenant. When it's ready, sync to
    Pinkfish: the same files run in the cloud, 24/7. Channel webhooks, public
    intake URLs, agents that act while you sleep.
  </p>
  <p>
    Production is durable, because IT can't depend on your laptop being awake.
  </p>

  <h2>Plain files. Yours, forever.</h2>
  <p>
    Open the project in any editor. Markdown and JSON. Diffs you can read.
    PRs you can review. Hand the repo to a terminal-native engineer and
    they're immediately productive — every file OpenIT writes is identical to
    what plain Claude Code would write. If you ever leave OpenIT, you walk
    out with your config.
  </p>

  <h2>Status</h2>
  <p>
    Public beta. macOS (Apple Silicon + Intel), signed and notarized — no
    first-launch warning. Linux and Windows builds follow.
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
